Review: A harrowing, breathtaking, sweeping, necessary masterpiece.

Movie: What's Love Got to Do with It?

Review: Clearly in the minority here, but I was really waiting for an emotional core or thread throughout, and I'm not quite sure it ever hit.
No notes, no comments, this was so joyous.
So powerful. Now excuse me while I go and acquaint myself with the rest of his oeuvre.

“For fantasy is true, of course. It isn’t factual, but it’s true. Children know that. Adults know it too and that’s precisely why many of them are afraid of fantasy. They know that its truth challenges, even threatens, all that is false, all that is phony, unnecessary, and trivial in the life they have let themselves be forced into living. They are afraid of dragons because they are afraid of freedom.”
A double whammy watching this and The Fabelmans practically back to back. Both, to me, devastating and difficult.
Such a delight to watch actors and directors so obviously having a blast with their craft.

Awestruck at the genuine wonder, belief in the medium of cinema (and technology), and lack of cynicism James Cameron brings in this giant sequel I don’t think anyone really wanted or thought we needed.
